   <titles>
      <title>Pasting Lemma: Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The essence of the Pasting Lemma is illustrated in the graphic below.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/PastingLemma.png"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>We start with two functions:</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>{\color{red} f\from \OCIntrvl{a}{b}\to \RNr}</latex>
                        </math>, and</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>{\color{blue} g\from \COIntrvl{b}{c}\to \RNr}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
            <para>
               <para.body>Now there is a two-step process which gives new information:</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>{\color{red} f(b)} = {\color{blue} g(b)}</latex>
                        </math>, then <math>
                           <latex>f</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>g</latex>
                        </math> can be pasted together to form a new function</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>h\from \OOIntrvl{a}{c} \longrightarrow \RNr</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>f</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>g</latex>
                        </math> are both continuous at <math>
                           <latex>b</latex>
                        </math>, so is <math>
                           <latex>h</latex>
                        </math>. â€“ Visibly: under this condition the pasted function does not make a jump at <math>
                           <latex>b</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ol>
         </block.body>
